    "reasoning": "The original module provided in the specification is: `assign out = (~sel & a) | (sel & b);`. \nAnalyzing the logic: \n- `a` is an 8-bit signal, `b` is an 8-bit signal, and `sel` is a 1-bit signal.\n- The expression `(~sel & a)` performs a bitwise AND between a 1-bit value (`~sel`) and an 8-bit value (`a`). In SystemVerilog, the 1-bit value will be zero-extended to 8 bits. If `sel` is 0, `~sel` is 1 (8'h01), so `~sel & a` results in `8'h01 & a`, which is only the LSB of `a` (if `a[0]` is 1) and zeros for all other bits. This is incorrect for an 8-bit multiplexer.\n- The same issue occurs with `(sel & b)`.\n- To fix this, the selection signal `sel` must be treated such that it selects the entire 8-bit bus. The correct implementation of a 2-to-1 multiplexer for an 8-bit bus is `out = sel ? b : a;` or using the bitwise logic with proper expansion: `out = (~{8{sel}} & a) | ({8{sel}} & b);`.\n- The simplest and most readable way to implement a multiplexer in SystemVerilog is using the conditional operator `? :`.\n\nAdvice to avoid syntax errors:\n1. Always ensure the bit-widths of operands in bitwise operations are compatible or understand how zero/sign extension works.\n2. When using `always @(*)`, ensure all signals read within the block are declared.\n3. Use the conditional operator `? :` for multiplexers to avoid bit-width mismatch errors common in bitwise logic.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input        logic sel,\n    input  logic [7:0] a,\n    input  logic [7:0] b,\n    output logic       out\n);\n\n    // The original bug was caused by bitwise operations between a 1-bit 'sel' and 8-bit 'a/b'.\n    // In Verilog, (~sel & a) would zero-extend ~sel, resulting in 8'h01 & a, which is not a mux.\n    // The correct way to implement a multiplexer is using the conditional operator.\n\n    assign out = sel ? b : a;\n\nendmodule"
}
